  <!-- ========== PATTERN 1: INDEPENDENT REGIONS ========== -->
  <category>
    <pattern>INDEPENDENT REGIONS</pattern>
    <template>
      <think>
        <set name="current_pattern">1</set>
        <set name="pattern_name">INDEPENDENT REGIONS</set>
        <set name="confidence">2</set>
      </think>
      <b>Pattern 1: INDEPENDENT REGIONS **</b>

      <b>Problem:</b> Metropolitan regions will not come to balance until each one
      is small and autonomous enough to be an independent sphere of culture.

      <b>Solution:</b> Work toward the evolution of independent regions in the world;
      each with a population between 2 and 10 million; each with its own natural
      and geographic boundaries; each with its own economy; each one autonomous
      and self-governing; each with a seat in a world government.

      <b>Key Numbers:</b> 2-10 million people per region, ~1000 regions worldwide

      <condition name="show_connections" value="true">
        <b>Following Patterns:</b>
        <srai>LIST FOLLOWING PATTERNS 1</srai>
      </condition>
    </template>
  </category>

  <category>
    <pattern>* INDEPENDENT REGION *</pattern>
    <template><srai>INDEPENDENT REGIONS</srai></template>
  </category>

  <category>
    <pattern>PATTERN 1</pattern>
    <template><srai>INDEPENDENT REGIONS</srai></template>
  </category>

  <!-- ========== PATTERN 2: DISTRIBUTION OF TOWNS ========== -->
  <category>
    <pattern>DISTRIBUTION OF TOWNS</pattern>
    <template>
      <think>
        <set name="current_pattern">2</set>
        <set name="pattern_name">DISTRIBUTION OF TOWNS</set>
        <set name="confidence">1</set>
      </think>
      <b>Pattern 2: THE DISTRIBUTION OF TOWNS *</b>

      <b>Problem:</b> If the population of a region is weighted too far toward
      small villages, modern civilization can never emerge; but if weighted too
      far toward big cities, the earth will go to ruin.

      <b>Solution:</b> Encourage a birth and death process for towns which creates:
      1. Population evenly distributed by size (logarithmic):
         - 1 town of 1,000,000
         - 10 towns of 100,000
         - 100 towns of 10,000
         - 1000 towns of 1,000
      2. Towns homogeneously distributed across the region.

      <b>Key Distances:</b>
      - 1M towns: 250 miles apart
      - 100K towns: 80 miles apart
      - 10K towns: 25 miles apart
      - 1K towns: 8 miles apart

      <condition name="show_connections" value="true">
        <b>Preceding:</b> <srai>PATTERN NAME 1</srai>
        <b>Following:</b> <srai>LIST FOLLOWING PATTERNS 2</srai>
      </condition>
    </template>
  </category>

  <category>
    <pattern>PATTERN 2</pattern>
    <template><srai>DISTRIBUTION OF TOWNS</srai></template>
  </category>

  <!-- ========== PATTERN 3: CITY COUNTRY FINGERS ========== -->
  <category>
    <pattern>CITY COUNTRY FINGERS</pattern>
    <template>
      <think>
        <set name="current_pattern">3</set>
        <set name="pattern_name">CITY COUNTRY FINGERS</set>
        <set name="confidence">2</set>
      </think>
      <b>Pattern 3: CITY COUNTRY FINGERS **</b>

      <b>Problem:</b> Continuous sprawling urbanization destroys life, and makes
      cities unbearable. But the sheer size of cities is also valuable and potent.

      <b>Solution:</b> Keep interlocking fingers of farmland and urban land, even
      at the center of the metropolis.
      - Urban fingers: never more than 1 mile wide
      - Farmland fingers: never less than 1 mile wide

      <b>Key Insight:</b> Everyone should be within 10 minutes' walk of countryside.

      <condition name="show_connections" value="true">
        <b>Preceding:</b> <srai>PATTERN NAME 2</srai>
        <b>Following:</b> <srai>LIST FOLLOWING PATTERNS 3</srai>
      </condition>
    </template>
  </category>

  <category>
